en\">Hard to give a definition for. Intuitively a &quot;natural kind&quot; rather than a collection of any old things, which a class is able to be, formally. At the meta level, universals are defined as positives, are disjoint with their siblings, have single asserted parents.</obo:IAO_0000116>\nsrc/ontology/imports/cteno_import.owl:9015:        <rdfs:label>&apos;causally downstream of&apos; and &apos;overlaps&apos; should be disjoint properties (a SWRL rule is required because these are non-simple properties).</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/cteno_import.owl:9071:        <rdfs:label>&apos;causally upstream of&apos; and &apos;overlaps&apos; should be disjoint properties (a SWRL rule is required because these are non-simple properties).</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/ceph_import.owl:393:        <obo:IAO_0000116>The original intent was to treat this as a macro that expands to &apos;in taxon&apos; only ?Y - however, this is not necessary if we instead have supplemental axioms that state that each pair of sibling tax have a disjointness axiom using the &apos;in taxon&apos; property - e.g.\nsrc/ontology/imports/ceph_import.owl:427:        <obo:IAO_0000115>A is spatially_disjoint_from B if and only if they have no parts in common</obo:IAO_0000115>\nsrc/ontology/imports/ceph_import.owl:428:        <obo:IAO_0000116>There are two ways to encode this as a shortcut relation. The other possibility to use an annotation assertion between two classes, and expand this to a disjointness axiom. </obo:IAO_0000116>\nsrc/ontology/imports/ceph_import.owl:433:        <rdfs:label>spatially disjoint from</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/ceph_import.owl:1140:        <owl:disjointUnionOf rdf:parseType=\"Collection\">\nsrc/ontology/imports/ceph_import.owl:1143:        </owl:disjointUnionOf>\nsrc/ontology/imports/ceph_import.owl:1308:        <owl:disjointWith rdf:resource=\"http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0008150\"/>\nsrc/ontology/imports/ceph_import.owl:3735:        <owl:disjointUni